## Starvation

Starvation, an unfortunately persistent element of the human condition, represents the most extreme manifestation of [malnutrition](/Malnutrition), characterized by a severe and sustained deficiency in caloric [energy](/Food_energy) intake—a deficit so profound it falls below the fundamental requirements necessary to sustain an organism's life. In the human context, this profound deprivation, when prolonged, precipitates irreversible damage to vital [organ](/Organ_(anatomy)) systems, ultimately culminating in [death](/Death). The specific terminology used to denote the collection of symptoms and effects resulting from such severe lack of sustenance is "inanition."

Starvation, while sometimes attributed to natural phenomena, is all too frequently a consequence of human actions. The deliberate [infliction of starvation](/Starvation_(crime)) upon a population is unequivocally recognized as a grave offense under [international criminal law](/International_criminal_law). Beyond mass atrocities, it can also be employed as a barbaric means of [torture](/Torture) or [execution](/Execution), a stark reminder of humanity's capacity for cruelty.

The [World Health Organization](/World_Health_Organization) (WHO), a global authority on public health, has consistently highlighted the dire reality that [hunger](/Hunger) remains the single gravest threat to the world's collective public health. Furthermore, the WHO emphasizes that [malnutrition](/Malnutrition), the broader category encompassing various deficiencies, stands as the predominant contributor to [child mortality](/Child_mortality), being implicated in approximately half of all deaths among children under the age of five. Undernutrition specifically acts as a significant contributory factor in the premature demise of 3.1 million children under five each year, a statistic that should haunt us all. Recent data from the WHO further underscores a grim stagnation, if not regression, in global efforts. While there have been isolated pockets of progress, such as reductions in stunting and increased exclusive breastfeeding rates, the overall picture remains alarming. The world has effectively been set back by 15 years, with levels of undernourishment mirroring those observed in 2008-2009. In 2023, estimates suggest between 713 and 757 million individuals faced undernourishment, representing a staggering increase of over 152 million people compared to 2019, when the mid-range estimate was 733 million. This isn't merely a statistic; it's a testament to systemic failures and ongoing global crises.

The visibly bloated stomach, often depicted in images of severe deprivation, is a hallmark symptom of a specific form of [protein-energy malnutrition](/Protein%E2%80%93energy_malnutrition) known as [kwashiorkor](/Kwashiorkor). The precise mechanisms underlying the development of kwashiorkor are complex and not yet fully elucidated. Historically, it was theorized to be primarily linked to diets characterized by a high intake of carbohydrates (such as [maize](/Maize)) but critically deficient in [protein](/Protein_(nutrient)). However, current understanding suggests a more intricate pathogenesis. While many individuals suffering from kwashiorkor do exhibit low [albumin](/Albumin) levels, this is now largely considered a consequence of the overall physiological stress and dysfunction, rather than the primary cause. Emerging research has pointed towards several potential contributing factors, including exposure to [aflatoxin](/Aflatoxin) poisoning, increased [oxidative stress](/Oxidative_stress) within the body, significant [immune dysregulation](/Immune_dysregulation), and profound alterations to the [gut microbiota](/Gut_microbiota). While therapeutic interventions can certainly alleviate the acute symptoms, such as the severe [weight loss](/Weight_loss) and pronounced [muscle](/Muscle) wasting that accompany the condition, the emphasis remains overwhelmingly on prevention as the most effective and humane strategy.

Without any form of sustenance, the average human being typically succumbs to the effects of starvation within approximately two months. However, the human body's capacity for survival, under extreme duress, can occasionally defy such averages. A notable, albeit exceptional, instance involved a patient who, under stringent [medical supervision](/Medical_supervision), remarkably survived without food for over a year—specifically, 382 days. This extraordinary [case](/Angus_Barbieri%27s_fast) highlights the complex interplay of physiological reserves and medical management. Generally, individuals with a leaner body composition can endure a loss of up to 18% of their [body mass](/Body_mass) before critical organ failure becomes imminent. Conversely, those with higher adipose tissue reserves, typically classified as obese, may tolerate a more significant depletion, potentially exceeding 20% of their initial body mass. Furthermore, biological sex appears to play a role in this grim calculus; females often exhibit a marginally longer survival duration than males, primarily due to their inherently higher average body fat content at comparable [Body Mass Index](/Body_Mass_Index) (BMI) levels, offering a slightly extended period for the body to metabolize its own tissues.

### Signs and symptoms

